      "title": "Solution of Exact Differential Equation ",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Exact Form&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>A differential equation of the form $\\text{M}\\left( \\text{x},\\text{y} \\right)\\text{dx}+\\text{N}\\left( \\text{x},\\text{y} \\right)\\text{dy}=0$ is said to be exact form if its left hand expression is the exact differential of some function i.e. $\\left( \\text{x},\\text{y} \\right)$.</p><p>i.e. $du=M.dx+N.dy$</p><p>It is a form which can be interpreted to get solution of DE. This form works by method of inspection and for that you require practice.</p><p>The following shortcuts will ease out your process</p><ol><li>$xdy+ydx=d\\left( xy \\right)$</li><li>$xdx+ydy=\\frac{1}{2}d\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)$</li><li>$\\frac{xdy-ydx}{{{x}^{2}}}=d\\left( \\frac{y}{x} \\right)$</li><li>$\\frac{\\text{ydx}-\\text{xdy}}{{{\\text{y}}^{2}}}=\\text{d}\\left( \\frac{\\text{x}}{\\text{y}} \\right)$ [remember these two by the dinominator in DE]</li><li>$\\frac{xdy-ydx}{xy}=d\\left[ \\text{log}\\left( \\frac{y}{x} \\right) \\right]$</li><li>$\\frac{ydx-xdy}{xy}=d\\left[ \\text{log}\\left( \\frac{x}{y} \\right) \\right]$</li><li>$\\frac{xdy-ydx}{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}=d\\left[ \\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\left( \\frac{y}{x} \\right) \\right]$</li><li>$\\frac{ydx-xdy}{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}=d\\left[ \\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\left( \\frac{x}{y} \\right) \\right]$</li><li>$\\frac{ydx+xdy}{xy}=d\\left[ \\text{log}\\left( xy \\right) \\right]$</li><li>$\\frac{xdy+ydx}{{{x}^{2}}{{y}^{2}}}=d\\left( \\frac{-1}{xy} \\right)$</li></ol><p><strong>Q) (a) $xdx+ydy+\\frac{xdy-ydx}{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}=0$ (b) $\\left( 1-{{x}^{2}}{{y}^{2}} \\right)dx=ydx+xdy$ (c) $\\left( 1+xy \\right)ydx+\\left( 1-xy \\right)xdy=0$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" width=\"377\" height=\"87\"></p><p>$\\Rightarrow &nbsp;$ DE becomes</p><p>$\\text{d}\\left[ \\frac{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}}{2} \\right]+\\text{d}\\left[ \\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\frac{\\text{y}}{\\text{x}} \\right]=0$</p><p>integrating this to get the solution.</p><p>$\\frac{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}{2}+\\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\frac{y}{x}=0$</p><p>(b) $\\left( 1-{{x}^{2}}{{y}^{2}} \\right)dx=ydx+xdy$</p><p>We know RHS is of teh form d[xy] and LHS also contains the term of xy. Rearranging</p><p>$\\text{dx}=\\frac{\\text{d}\\left[ \\text{xy} \\right]}{1-{{\\text{x}}^{2}}{{\\text{y}}^{2}}}$</p><p>On RHS putting xy = t</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; \\Rightarrow \\text{d}[\\text{xy}]=\\text{dt} \\\\ &amp; \\Rightarrow \\text{dx}=\\frac{\\text{dt}}{1-{{\\text{t}}^{2}}} \\\\ \\end{align}$</p><p>integrating $ \\int{\\text{dx}}=\\int{\\frac{\\text{dt}}{1-{{\\text{t}}^{2}}}}$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow &nbsp;\\text{x}=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{log}\\left| \\frac{1+\\text{t}}{1-\\text{t}} \\right|+\\text{c}$</p><p>replacing t by xy</p><p>$\\Rightarrow &nbsp;\\text{x}=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{log}\\left| \\frac{1+\\text{xy}}{1-\\text{xy}} \\right|+\\text{c}$</p><p>(c) $\\left( 1+xy \\right)ydx+\\left( 1-xy \\right)xdy=0$</p><p>at first look we cannot see any exact form over here but let us wait.</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; ydx+x{{y}^{2}}dx+xdy-{{x}^{2}}ydy=0 \\\\ &amp; (xdy+ydx)+xy(ydx-xdy)=0...(i) \\ \\end{align}$</p><p>now this can be in exact form</p><p>$d\\left[ xy \\right]=xdy+ydx$</p><p>and $d\\left[ \\text{log}\\left( \\frac{x}{y} \\right) \\right]=\\frac{ydx-xdy}{xy}$</p><p>So arranging for DE</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; \\frac{(xdy+ydx)}{xy}+(ydx-xdy)=0 \\\\ &amp; \\left( \\frac{xdy+ydx}{{{(xy)}^{2}}} \\right)+\\frac{(ydx-xdy)}{(xy)}=0 \\\\ &amp; \\underbrace{\\frac{\\text{d}(\\text{xy})}{{{(\\text{xy})}^{2}}}}_{\\begin{smallmatrix} \\text{ his part } \\\\ \\text{ xy }=\\text{t},\\text{d}[\\text{xy}]=\\text{dt} \\end{smallmatrix}}+\\text{d}\\left[ \\log \\left( \\frac{\\text{x}}{\\text{y}} \\right) \\right]=0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\frac{\\text{dt}}{{{\\text{t}}^{2}}}+\\text{d}\\left( \\log \\left( \\frac{\\text{x}}{\\text{y}} \\right) \\right)=0 \\\\ \\end{align}$</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} -\\frac{1}{\\text{t}}+\\log \\left( \\frac{\\text{x}}{\\text{y}} \\right)+\\text{c}=0 \\\\ \\Rightarrow \\log \\left( \\frac{\\text{x}}{\\text{y}} \\right)-\\frac{1}{\\text{xy}}+\\text{c}=0 \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Q) (a) $ydx+\\frac{y}{x}dx+\\text{sin}ydx+xdy+\\text{log}xdy+x\\text{cos}ydy=0$</p><p>(b) $\\frac{xdx+ydy}{xdy-ydx}=\\sqrt{\\frac{{{a}^{2}}-{{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}}}{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}}$ (c) $\\frac{dy}{dx}+\\frac{y}{x}=\\frac{1}{{{(1+\\text{log }x+\\text{log}y)}^{2}}}$</p><p>Solution:</p><p>(a) $ydx+\\frac{y}{x}dx+\\text{sin}ydx+xdy+\\text{log}xdy+x\\text{cos}ydy=0_{{}}^{{}}$</p><p>arranging them to pair, to form exact forms</p><p>$\\underbrace{(ydx+xdy)}_{d[xy]}+\\underbrace{(\\sin ydx+x\\cos ydy)}_{d[x\\sin y]}+\\underbrace{\\left( \\frac{y}{x}dx+\\log xdy \\right)}_{d[y\\log x]})=0$</p><p>why $d\\left[ x\\text{sin}y \\right]$ ?</p><p>differentiate $\\left( x\\text{sin}y \\right)$ w.r.t. x &amp; y separately</p><p>$\\text{d}[\\text{x}\\sin \\text{y}]=\\underbrace{\\sin \\text{ydx}}_{\\text{w}\\text{.r}\\text{.t}\\text{. x}}+\\underbrace{\\text{x}\\cos \\text{ydy}}_{\\text{w}\\text{.r}\\text{.t}\\text{. x}}$</p><p>so integrating the DE formed</p><p>$\\int{\\text{d}}[\\text{xy}]+\\int{\\text{d}}[\\text{x}\\sin \\text{y}]+\\int{\\text{d}}[\\text{y}\\log \\text{x}]=0$</p><p>$xy+x\\sin y+y\\log x=0$</p><p>(b) $\\frac{xdx+ydy}{xdy-ydx}=\\sqrt{\\frac{{{a}^{2}}-{{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}}}{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}}$</p><p>$\\frac{xdx+ydy}{xdy-ydx}=\\sqrt{\\frac{{{a}^{2}}-\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)}{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}}$</p><p>also we know $ xdx+ydy=d\\left[ \\frac{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}{2} \\right]$</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{d}\\left[ \\frac{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}}{2} \\right]}{2}=\\sqrt{\\frac{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}-\\left( {{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}} \\right)}{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}}\\{\\text{xdy}-\\text{ydx}\\}}$</p><p>divding both sides by ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}$, because</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; \\frac{xdy-ydx}{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}=d\\left[ {{\\tan }^{-1}}\\left[ \\frac{y}{x} \\right] \\right] \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\frac{1}{2}\\frac{d\\left[ {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right]}{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{{{a}^{2}}-\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)}{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}}\\left( \\frac{xdy-ydx}{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}} \\right) \\\\ &amp; \\frac{1}{2}\\frac{d\\left[ {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right]}{\\sqrt{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}\\sqrt{{{a}^{2}}-\\left( {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}} \\right)}}=d\\left[ {{\\tan }^{-1}}\\left( \\frac{y}{x} \\right) \\right] \\\\ \\end{align}$</p><p>taking terms of $\\left( {{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}} \\right)$ on LHS</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; put{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}={{t}^{2}}onLHS \\\\ &amp; \\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{2}\\frac{2\\text{tdt}}{\\sqrt{{{\\text{t}}^{2}}}\\sqrt{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}-{{\\text{t}}^{2}}}}=\\text{d}\\left( {{\\tan }^{-1}}\\left( \\frac{\\text{y}}{\\text{x}} \\right) \\right) \\\\ &amp; \\Rightarrow \\frac{\\text{dt}}{\\sqrt{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}-{{\\text{t}}^{2}}}}=\\text{d}\\left[ {{\\tan }^{-1}}\\left( \\frac{\\text{y}}{\\text{x}} \\right) \\right] \\\\ \\end{align}$</p><p>integrating &amp; using standard formula's</p><p>$\\text{si}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\left( \\frac{t}{a} \\right)=\\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\left( \\frac{y}{x} \\right)+c$</p><p>$\\therefore$ The solution is</p><p>$\\text{si}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\left( \\frac{\\sqrt{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}}{a} \\right)=\\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\left( \\frac{y}{x} \\right)+c$</p><p>(c) $\\frac{dy}{dx}+\\frac{y}{x}=\\frac{1}{{{(1+\\text{log}x+\\text{log}y)}^{2}}}$</p><p>again at first look this looks like a non-exact form</p><p>$\\frac{dy}{dx}+\\frac{y}{x}=\\frac{1}{{{(1+\\text{log}xy)}^{2}}} \\text{ using } \\text{ log }a+\\text{log}b=\\text{log}ab$</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; \\frac{xdy+ydx}{xdx}=\\frac{1}{{{(1+\\log (xy))}^{2}}} \\\\ &amp; \\Rightarrow (xdy+ydx){{(1+\\log xy)}^{2}}=xdx \\\\ \\end{align}$</p><p>and we know $d\\left[ xy \\right]=xdy+ydx$</p><p>putting $xy=t$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow \\text{d}\\left[ \\text{t} \\right]{{(1+\\text{logt})}^{2}}=\\text{xdx}$</p><p>integrating both sides</p><p>$\\int{1}\\cdot {{(1+\\log \\text{t})}^{2}}\\text{dt}=\\int{\\text{xd}}x$</p><p>solving LHS by parts</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; {{(1+\\log t)}^{2}}\\cdot t-\\int{t}\\cdot \\frac{2(1+\\log t)}{t}dt=\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{2}+c \\\\ &amp; \\text{t}.{{(1+\\log \\text{t})}^{2}}-2\\int{(1+\\log \\text{t})}\\text{dt}=\\frac{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}{2}+\\text{c }...\\text{(i)} \\\\ \\end{align}$</p><p>Now solving</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; =\\int{(1+\\log t)}dt=\\int{d}t+\\int{\\log }tdt \\\\ &amp; =t+\\int{\\log }tdt \\\\ &amp; =t+(t\\log t-t) \\\\ &amp; =t\\log t \\\\ \\end{align}$</p><p>putting this value back in (i)</p><p>$ \\text{ t}\\text{. } {{(1+\\text{log}t)}^{2}}-2t\\text{log}t=\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{2}+c$</p><p>$\\therefore$ solution is</p><p>$xy{{(1+\\text{log}xy)}^{2}}-2xy\\text{log}xy=\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{2}+c$</p>",
      "position": 0,
